‚ÄúLet me tell you who are the children of my Lebanon.

They are farmers who would turn the fallow field into garden and grove. They are the shepherds who lead their flocks through the valleys to be fattened for your table meat and your woolens. They are the vine-pressers who press the grape to wine and boil it to syrup. They are the parents who tend the nurseries, the mothers who spin the silken yarn. They are the husbands who harvest the wheat and the wives who gather the sheaves. They are the builders, the potters, the weavers and the bell-casters. They are the poets who pour their souls in new cups. They are those who migrate with nothing but courage in their hearts and strength in their arms but who return with wealth in their hands and a wreath of glory upon their heads. They are the victorious wherever they go and loved and respected wherever they settle. They are the ones born in huts but who died in palaces of learning. These are the children of Lebanon; they are the lamps that cannot be snuffed by the wind and the salt which remains unspoiled through the ages. They are the ones who are steadily moving toward perfection, beauty, and truth.

You have your Lebanon and I have my Lebanon.‚Äù -Khalil Gibran, 1920

(Please swipe and read in its entirety) As I was landing back on Texas soil today, I looked out the window and noticed the rays of sun were especially breathtaking. I tweeted this picture with the caption ‚ÄúGod loves Texas.‚Äù It wasn‚Äôt until 20 minutes ago that I learned about the Santa Fe school shooting here in my adopted home state, and my heart shattered. God wasn‚Äôt shining down on Texas, he was mourning for it. I try to stay out of politics and keep my opinion to myself. I have always been a republican, I have always loved guns, I have always felt like the right to protection with a weapon was my given right as an American; but after seeing an interview with one of the survivors of the #SantaFe shooting who said she ‚Äúalways expected this. That it (school shootings) was happening everywhere, and it was just a matter of time before it happened at my school,‚Äù I can‚Äôt be neutral anymore. Its my responsibility as someone with influence and a following, as a Texan, as a citizen of the human race, to speak up and say something. We are failing our children. Just take a moment to think about what she said... We need to DO SOMETHING. Congress needs to DO SOMETHING. Trump needs to DO SOMETHING. When in the midst of a revolution, every minor action matters, and here is my contribution: I will relinquish my right to bear arms, in solidarity with our massacred youth. I don‚Äôt need to protect myself, I need to protect them. This gun rack will remain empty, just like the beds of hundreds of kids who have died to date. My heart weeps for the parents, the siblings, and the survivors - who‚Äôs innocence died, and should be mourned just the same. I urge you to #DoSomething, what‚Äôs more important? Your self righteous entitlement over a line on a piece of paper from 142 years ago, or the lives of our children?
